> It's kind of a long-shot and, at a *guess*, it's not relevant to
> your problem, but I'd still check the fuel pressure. Go down to your
> local Ace Hardware and get a water pressure gauge that reads up to
> 45 lbs. Get a brass hose barb that screws on to the gauge with a
> 1/4" barb. Get a length of FI hose and a couple of hose clamps. For
> $15 - $20 you're in business and can ensure that fuel pressure
> *isn't* the problem. It's one of those "tools" you use once every
> year or two and the price is right.

